te about the origins of America's racial and urban crisis. Challenging previous analysts' near-exclusive focus on northern "rust-belt" cities devastated by de-industrialization, Josh Sides asserts that the cities to which black southerners migrated profoundly affected how they fared. He shows how L.A.'s diverse racial composition, dispersive geography, and dynamic postwar economy often created opportunities—and limits—quite different from those encountered by blacks in the urban North.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a1960s.  aafrican americans.  ablack americans.  ablack experience.  ablack migrants.  acalifornia.  acritical history.  adeindustrialization.  adiscussion books.  agreat depression.  ahistorical.  alos angeles.  amodern history.  amodern los angeles.  anonfiction.  apostwar economy.  arace riots.  aracial diversity.  aracial issues.  aregional differences.  aregional history.  asocial inequality.  aurban america.  aurban crisis.  aurban landscape.  aurban studies.  awestward movement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023841140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093986840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939868423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939868/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY